        "sender_full_name": "Rémi Bottinelli",
        "timestamp": 1672578676
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not that bad, but I was wondering, because I would think it's something people see quite often.</p>",
        "id": 318856629,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémi Bottinelli",
        "timestamp": 1672578770
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Given that this tactic would generate <a href=\"https://oeis.org/A000670\">https://oeis.org/A000670</a> goals (which is quite fast-growing), I don't think you would ever use it for more than 3 variables</p>",
        "id": 318857306,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1672579164
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, not worth it for three, and inpractical for more, hence just not worth it?</p>",
        "id": 318858871,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémi Bottinelli",
        "timestamp": 1672579970
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you need to check all 13 cases separately? I had to do something similar recently for the proof of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/not_monotone_not_antitone_iff_exists_lt_lt\">docs#not_monotone_not_antitone_iff_exists_lt_lt</a>, and I only distinguished 10 cases instead of the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>169</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">13^2 = 169</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">169</span></span></span></span> cases I would have needed naively (the number of ways of ordering <code>a</code>, <code>b</code>, <code>c</code>, <code>d</code> knowing that <code>a &lt; b</code>, <code>c &lt; d</code>, times the number of ways of ordering <code>f a</code>, <code>f b</code>, <code>f c</code>, <code>f d</code> knowing that <code>f a &lt; f b</code>, <code>f d &lt; f c</code>).</p>",
        "id": 318858895,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1672579988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well: it's to show that the _signed_ variation function on a path is additive, i.e.  <code>variation $ Icc a c = variation $ Icc a b + variation $ Icc b c</code>. I already know swapping the endpoints reverses the sign, so I can probably wlog some cases for others, but I don't know if it's not easier just to treat all cases separately.</p>",
        "id": 318859272,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémi Bottinelli",
        "timestamp": 1672580197
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, can you do something with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/set.interval\">docs#set.interval</a> maybe?</p>",
        "id": 318860120,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1672580669
    },
    {
